Question 1 [15 marks]

Download vaso.data from Canvas this contains the vasoconstriction dataset from lectures. The explanatory variables are Volume and Rate, and the response variable is Response.

Q 1 (a) [6 marks]

Write down the JAGS model to perform logistic regression on this data. Centre the explanatory variables, and use the probit link function.

model="model

{   
        # Priors
        
        beta0 ~ dunif(-1000, 1000)
        beta1 ~ dunif(-1000, 1000)
        beta2 ~ dunif(-1000, 1000)
        
        # Sampling distribution
        
        for(i in 1:length(Response))
        {
            probit(p[i])<-beta0 +beta1*(Volume[i])+beta2*(Rate[i])
            Response[i] ~ dbin(p[i],1)
        
        }
          
}
"

data=read.table("vaso.data",header=TRUE)

# vol.mean is mean of Volume, rat.mean is mean of Rate
vol.mean=mean(data$Volume)
rat.mean=mean(data$Rate)


data2=data.frame(Volume=data$Volume-vol.mean,Rate=data$Rate-rat.mean,Response=data$Response)



# Variables to monitor
variable_names = c("beta0", "beta1", "beta2")

# How many proper steps?
steps = 100000

# Thinning?
thin = 10

library("rjags")
## Loading required package: coda
## Linked to JAGS 4.3.1
## Loaded modules: basemod,bugs
# Create a JAGS model object
jm = jags.model(textConnection(model), data2)
## Compiling model graph
##    Resolving undeclared variables
##    Allocating nodes
## Graph information:
##    Observed stochastic nodes: 39
##    Unobserved stochastic nodes: 3
##    Total graph size: 256
## 
## Initializing model
# Do some MCMC
results = coda.samples(jm, variable_names, steps, thin=thin)

# Extract chains as data frame
results = as.data.frame(results[[1]])

Prediction

We will now cover how to use JAGS to make a prediction of a new data point. It involves adding a new variable to the JAGS model to specify the probability distribution of the new point, conditional on all the parameters (and, if necessary , conditional on the previous pointsthis would occur in time series modelling, for example). Almost always, the distribution assumed for the new data point should be the same as for the previous data points.

In regression models , you need to specify values for the explanatory variables for the new point, or it wont work.

Q1 (c)

  1. [5 marks] Suppose ten trials are going to be conducted with Volume=1.0 and Rate=2.0. Write JAGS code to predict r, the number of successes out of these ten trials. What is the most probable value of r and what is its probability?
model="model

{   
        # Priors
        
        beta0 ~ dunif(-1000, 1000)
        beta1 ~ dunif(-1000, 1000)
        beta2 ~ dunif(-1000, 1000)
        
        # Sampling distribution
        
        for(i in 1:length(Response))
        {
            probit(p[i])<-beta0 +beta1*Volume[i]+beta2*Rate[i]
            Response[i] ~ dbin(p[i],1)
        
        }
        
        probit(p_new)<-beta0 + beta1*1 + beta2*2
        Response_new ~ dbin(p_new,1)
          
}
"
# Variables to monitor
variable_names = c("beta0", "beta1", "beta2","Response_new")

# Create a JAGS model object
jm = jags.model(textConnection(model), data2)
## Compiling model graph
##    Resolving undeclared variables
##    Allocating nodes
## Graph information:
##    Observed stochastic nodes: 39
##    Unobserved stochastic nodes: 4
##    Total graph size: 262
## 
## Initializing model
results=coda.samples(jm,variable_names,steps, thin=thin)

results=as.data.frame(results[[1]])

The results look like a binomial distribution.

hist(results$Response_new)

The number of success out of 10 trials is r, r =10.according to the histogram plot.

# probit_p is probit(p) for Volume=1.0, Rate=2.0

probit_p=mean(results$beta0)+mean(results$beta1*1)+mean(results$beta2*2)
probit_p

### Question 2 [20 marks]



Bike sharing systems have become rather common in cities around the world. Using these systems,
people are able to rent a bike from a one location and return it to a different place on an as-needed
basis. The data set for this question was originally provided to a machine learning competition from
Capital Bikeshare. We removed some variables to keep the analysis simple. The question is about
finding a predictive model for the number of bike rentals in an hour for a given day.


The data set bike.csv contains the following variables:


season: seasons (1: spring, 2: summer, 3: fall, 4: winter)
yr: year (0: 2011, 1: 2012)

mnth: month (1 to 12)

hr: hour of the day (0 to 23)

holiday: whether it is holiday 1 or not 0.

weekday: day of the week (0 to 6), i.e. Sunday to Saturday

weathersit: 

 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy
*+ 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist
 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered
clouds


windspeed: Normalized wind speed. The values are divided by 67 (max)


cnt: count of total rental bikes including both casual and registered




####   Q2 (a)
*
You may assume the data set is clean for this question.

Q2 (e)

  1. [3 marks] Repeat parts (c) and (d) with a negative binomial model, and identify which model is preferred using the AIC values, the residual deviance, and the diagnostic plots.

ANSWER:

  • Residuals vs Fitted:

The line is quite level and straight, hence, the residuals are constant which is similar with poisson diagnostic plot.

  • Q-Q plot:

The line has a little bit non-linear signs , since the line is not very straight. It means that the Std Pearsons residuals quantiles are not quite match theoritical one. Can do transformation for explanatory variables. This QQ plot is similar with the implication of poisson model.

  • Scale location:

The line is a little bit trending down , which shows different trending sighs with that of possion model. It means the absolute residuals narrows over x-axis.
Whereas in poisson model, the line in this plot is trending up.

  • Cooks distance:

9124 and 6301 , 586 have highest cooks distance which all are less than 0.5 and 1. It means these points should have potential of high leverage. 9124 and 6301 points are different with what we got from poisson model.

  • Residuals vs Leverage:

6301 has highest residual against 9124 and 586 points, moreover, 6301 has quite high Cooks distance , but 6301 has low x value, hence 6301 has medium leverage. 586 has high leverage though 586s residual is low, since its x-value is high.. 9124 has high leverage though its residual is low, since its x-value is higt.

  • Cooks dist vs Leverage* hii/(1-hii):

the average hii=(k+1)/n =10/17376=0.00057, hii for 586 is around 0.5 which is much higher than average hii, hence 586 should has high leverage. hii for 9124 is 0.3 which is much higher than average, hence, 9124 should have high leverage. hii for 6301 is around average, 6301 has low leverage as this plot shows.

Which model is preferred?

negative binomial is preferred. The reason is as below:

  • AIC:

AIC for poisson is: 708502, for negative binomial is: 189015, 189502 is much less than 708502, hence, negative binomial is much preferred in the sense of smaller AIC.

  • Residual deviance:

for poisson is:597499 , whereas for negative binomial is: 18571, 18571 is much less than 597499. Hence, negative binomial model is preferred in terms of reducing the residual deviance, closer to max. model.

  • Diagnostic plot:

in Scale location plot , the lines for negative binomial model is relatively level , it shows a good signs of constant variance for residuals. Whereas the lines in poisson model is trending up, it means the variance of absolute residual is increasing, it is not a good signs for a goodness of model. Other plots showed not significant signs of differet of two models.

Q3 (b) [6 marks] Using the estimated coefficients

from the best model in (a), tell a story about when, and under what conditions, more people use the bike share system.

ANSWER:

  • For the best model,

hr thie explanatory variable

from 1 to 6 (midnight to early morning) , their coefs. are negative, it means this time slots would decrease the bike rental. The coefs varied from hr=1 to hr=6, with coefs increased, the bike rental would decrease. All the rest of coef for hr other than the above time slot has positive impact on bike rental due to positive coef. The coefs for different time increases, corespondingly the bike rental would increase. 8am , 5pm and 6pm these 3 busy hour has the most higt level positive influence on bike rental respectively, this time slot increase bike rental mostly.

  • mnth

all of mnth has positive coef, it means the bike rental would increase if the coef of mnth increases. From 6 to 8 ( Jun to August) in mid year have the most higt level positive influence on bike rental , since 6, 7 and 8 (Jun, July , August ) has the 3 highest coefs within mnth group. In this 3 months ,the bike rental would be increased mostly.

  • season

All the coefs for season is positive which means the season has positive impact on the bike rental. seaon 4 is winter . From the coef. comparison, winter would increase the bike rental more than the other summer and fall. As season 1 is spring which is included in Intercept. The coef of winter shows the positive signs that season 4 (winter) would increase bike rental mostly comparing with other seasons.

  • weathersit

coefs of weathersit (2,3,4) is negative, it means 2-4 weathersit would decrease the bike rental.

Weathersit 1 is included in Intercept, hence the weather 1 ( clear) Clear weather would increase the bike rental comparing with other weather.

  • weekday

Coefs for weekday 1 to weekday 5 ( weekdays) are all negative which means busy working weekday would decrease the bike rental. weekday0 (Sunday) would have positive impact on the bike rental. The weekday6 has positive coef (coef 0.02) but no significant. Hence, generally speaking, weekday0 ( Sunday) would increase the bike rental.

  • windspeed

coef of windspeed is negative, bear them in mind that windspeed is not a factor, as a result , the windspeed increases 0.12, the bike rental would decrease by 0.12 * a unit of bike rental.

  • yr1

yr1 is 2012, 2012 have positive impact on the bike rental. Hence, yr1 (2012) would increase the bike rental more than yr0 (2011).
